---
layout: layouts/base.njk
order: 6
resType: demo
kicker: Demo
resOrder: 1
listTitle: "A model running in your browser."
blurb: "A 1-bit, 1.7-billion-parameter model triages support messages entirely on your GPU via WebGPU — nothing you type leaves the tab."
title: Live demo
description: Run a language model in this page — a 1-bit, 1.7-billion-parameter model triages support messages entirely in your browser on WebGPU. Nothing you type leaves your device. A working illustration of sovereign, on-device inference.
ogType: website
faq:
  - q: Does anything I type leave my browser?
    a: >-
      No. The model weights are downloaded once from Hugging Face and cached by your
      browser; after that, all computation happens on your own GPU via WebGPU. Your
      messages are never sent to any server — there is no server.
  - q: Why is the model only 0.24 GB?
    a: >-
      Bonsai-1.7B stores its weights at roughly 1.125 bits each (packed sign bits plus
      small group scales) instead of 16 bits — about 14× smaller than the same model in
      FP16. Extreme quantization is one of the levers that makes sovereign, on-premise
      deployment affordable; our <a href="/concepts/quantization/">quantization
      concept page</a> covers the trade-offs.
  - q: Is this the model sysf.io deploys for clients?
    a: >-
      No — Bonsai-1.7B is an independent open model by Prism ML, used here purely to
      demonstrate on-device inference. Client systems are built on
      <a href="/platform/">Apertus, fine-tuned on your data and evaluated against your
      task</a>; the pattern is the same, the model is yours.
  - q: What do I need to run it?
    a: >-
      A desktop browser with WebGPU (recent Chrome or Edge) and a GPU. The first run
      downloads ~237 MB, one time. If WebGPU isn't available the page will say so —
      nothing breaks.
---
