      {v:"32k", label:"Token context window", sub:"The full Qwen3-1.7B context length, executed on your GPU"},
      {v:"0", label:"Bytes of data egress", sub:"Weights come down from Hugging Face; nothing you type goes anywhere"}
    ] %}
    <div class="mt-10">{{ statBand(stats) }}</div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- From demo to production -->
<section class="container-x py-16 md:py-20">
  <div class="grid gap-10 md:grid-cols-12">
    <div class="md:col-span-5">
      {{ sectionHead("From demo to production", "The pattern is the product.", "") }}
    </div>
    <div class="space-y-5 text-[15px] prose-muted md:col-span-7">
      <p>
        What you just used is a pattern: a small, task-scoped model, quantized to fit the
        hardware you actually have, running where the data lives. In client work we apply
        the same pattern with different ingredients — <a class="underline" href="/platform/">Apertus</a>,
        the open Swiss model, fine-tuned on your data, deployed in your jurisdiction, and
        held to an <a class="underline" href="/concepts/evaluation/">evaluation bar</a> agreed
        before the project starts.
      </p>
      <p>
        If your organisation has an inbox, a document stream or a form pipeline that
        people currently sort by hand, that's usually the right first project: narrow,
        measurable, and sovereign from day one.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

